{
  "answer": "**The translation of *Manusmṛti* (Manusmṛti) chapter 7 in this corpus does not contain a specific verse that explicitly lists seven elements (also called \"limbs\" or *aṅgas*, or \"constituents\" or *prakṛtis*) of the state.**\n\nChapter 7 focuses on the origin and duties of kings, punishment (*daṇḍa*), counsel, forts, taxes, and political expedients, but makes no numbered reference to seven state elements.[^1] The immediately following verses—labeled Mn_7.156–157 but appearing at the start of the chapter 8 file due to continuous numbering in this translation—refer to \"constituents\" (*prakṛtis*) of the *maṇḍala* (circle of states) and then list **five** others: \"minister, kingdom, fortress, treasury, and army.\"[^2][^3]\n\nThis echoes Arthashastra-style state theory but does not enumerate seven there either (the standard seven are typically: king, minister, territory/people, fort, treasury, army, ally). For an explicit list of **seven limbs of the state** (*rāṣṭra-aṅgāni*), see instead *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* 1.353: \"the king, the minister, the people, the fort, the treasury, the army, and the allies.\"[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, chapter 7, full text (86 paragraphs/verses). [Chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti* Mn_7.156[157M], paragraph p-7a95d2. [Paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-7a95d2).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti* Mn_7.157[158M], paragraph p-4d605c. [Paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-4d605c).\n\n[^4]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* 1.353, paragraph p-312e84. [Paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-312e84).",
